LANGCHAIN AND LANGGRAPH FLOW DIAGRAMS
====================================


1. LangChain Basic Flow
-----------------------

LangChain is mainly used to call and work with LLMs.

Flow:

    +-------------+
    | User Input  |
    +-------------+
           |
           v
    +-------------+
    |   Prompt    |
    +-------------+
           |
           v
    +-------------+
    |     LLM     |
    +-------------+
           |
           v
    +-------------+
    |  Response   |
    +-------------+


In simple words:

    User asks question -> LangChain sends it to model -> Model gives answer


2. LangGraph Basic Flow
-----------------------

LangGraph is used to control a workflow using nodes and edges.

Flow:

    +-------+       +---------+       +---------+       +-----+
    | START | ----> | Node 1  | ----> | Node 2  | ----> | END |
    +-------+       +---------+       +---------+       +-----+


In simple words:

    START -> run one function -> run next function -> END


3. Difference Between LangChain and LangGraph
---------------------------------------------

    +------------------+      +--------------------------+
    |    LangChain     |      |        LangGraph         |
    +------------------+      +--------------------------+
    | Calls LLMs       |      | Controls workflow        |
    | Handles prompts  |      | Uses nodes and edges     |
    | Uses tools       |      | Supports branching       |
    | Gets responses   |      | Maintains graph state    |
    +------------------+      +--------------------------+


Easy memory:

    LangChain = AI model call
    LangGraph = AI workflow control


4. Your chat.py Flow
--------------------

This file has a simple straight-line graph.

    +-------+       +----------+       +------------+       +-----+
    | START | ----> | Chatbot  | ----> | samplenode | ----> | END |
    +-------+       +----------+       +------------+       +-----+


What happens:

    1. START
    2. Chatbot node calls Groq LLM
    3. samplenode adds "Sample Message Appended"
    4. END


State flow:

    Initial State:
    {
        message: ["Hi, My name is Amol Sawant"]
    }

           |
           v

    After Chatbot:
    {
        message: [
            "Hi, My name is Amol Sawant",
            AI response
        ]
    }

           |
           v

    After samplenode:
    {
        message: [
            "Hi, My name is Amol Sawant",
            AI response,
            "Sample Message Appended"
        ]
    }


5. Your chat2.py Conditional Flow
---------------------------------

This file has a conditional graph.

                       answer is good
                     +----------------+
                     |                |
                     v                |
    +-------+    +---------+    +----------+    +-----+
    | START | -> | chatbot | -> | endnode  | -> | END |
    +-------+    +---------+    +----------+    +-----+
                     |
                     |
                     | answer is not good
                     v
              +----------------+
              | chatbot_gemini |
              +----------------+
                     |
                     v
              +----------+    +-----+
              | endnode  | -> | END |
              +----------+    +-----+


What happens:

    1. START
    2. chatbot node calls OpenRouter model
    3. evaluate_response checks state["is_good"]
    4. If is_good is True, go to endnode
    5. If is_good is False, go to chatbot_gemini fallback
    6. END


State flow:

    Initial State:
    {
        user_query: "Hey, What is 2+2 ?"
    }

           |
           v

    After chatbot:
    {
        user_query: "Hey, What is 2+2 ?",
        llm_output: "2 + 2 equals 4.",
        is_good: True
    }

           |
           v

    evaluate_response decides:

        if is_good == True:
            go to endnode

        else:
            go to chatbot_gemini


